    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's focus on the soil pH adjustment for your tomato plants. To test your soil's pH, you'll need a soil test kit, which you can find at most garden centers. Once you have the results, here's what you can do:\n\n1. If your soil pH is too acidic (below 6.0), you'll want to add lime. Apply the lime according to the package instructions, usually by spreading it evenly over the soil surface and then working it into the top few inches of soil. Water the area well after application.\n\n2. If your soil pH is too alkaline (above 7.0), you'll need to add sulfur. Similar to lime, apply the sulfur as directed on the package, mix it into the soil, and water it in.\n\n3. After adding either lime or sulfur, wait for a few weeks and retest your soil's pH to ensure it's within the optimal range for tomatoes, which is between 6.0 and 6.8.\n\n4. Once your soil pH is balanced, your tomato plants should be able to absorb nutrients more effectively, leading to healthier growth and better yields.\n\nRemember, it's important to follow the specific instructions for the products you",
